Ed, yours looks ok for me. Am I right it is equivalent with mine except for the following differences:
1) The analyzer is not a top level class
2) The override hooks are renamed
3) You leave it to the implementor of the sub class to manage the changes (clever)
4) It is generics based.

As I said, it seems to work for me. The new CDO will offer the possibility to transparently version the object space and allows to "time travel" through the repository history. The new design completely separates the object's persistent state into the immutable concept of a CDORevision so that during time travel (and also during update of the HEAD version from remote changes) only the pointer from the CDOObject to its CDORevision must be changed. A CDORevision is not aware of Ecore at all because it must be transfered over the network and stored on the server where there is no EMF (at least not necessarily). CDOObjects have a unique (in the server repository) long ID and CDORevisions store the IDs of the target object for references.

This new feature (and general flaws in the old design) led me to choose a different strategy of integration with EMF. CDOObjectImpl is derived from EStoreEObjectImpl and delegates to a singleton EStore instance which is responsible for:
a) translating the Ecore related arguments into CDO equivalents (CDOPackage, CDOClass and CDOFeature)
b) handling containment changes
c) references to EObjects in arguments are converted into CDO IDs of the target objects
d) the CDORevision of the object argument is determined through a state machine which manages the CDOObjects state (TRANSIENT, NEW, DIRTY, CLEAN, PROXY, ...). if for example a write access is to be prepared for a CLEAN object the state machine copies the CDORevision, increases the version and registers the object with the CDOTransaction.
e) delegates the EStore method to a CDORevision method:

  public Object EStore.set(InternalEObject eObject, EStructuralFeature eFeature, int index, Object value)

  is delegated to

  public Object CDORevision.set(CDOFeature feature, int index, Object value)

f) converting CDO IDs for references of the resulting CDORevision back to CDOObjects (EObjects)

Here is an example of the set() method:

  public Object set(InternalEObject eObject, EStructuralFeature eFeature, int index, Object value)
  {
    CDOObjectImpl cdoObject = (CDOObjectImpl)eObject;
    CDOFeatureImpl cdoFeature = EMFUtil.getCDOFeature(eFeature);
    if (TRACER.isEnabled())
    {
      TRACER.format("set({0}, {1}, {2}, {3})", cdoObject, cdoFeature, index, value);
    }

    if (cdoFeature.isReference())
    {
      handleContainmentAdd(cdoObject, cdoFeature, value);
      value = convertToID(cdoObject.cdoAdapter(), value);
    }

    CDORevisionImpl revision = getRevisionForWriting(cdoObject);
    Object result = revision.set(cdoFeature, index, value);
    if (cdoFeature.isReference())
    {
      result = convertToObject(cdoObject.cdoAdapter(), result);
    }

    return result;
  }

As mentioned above within a transaction CDORevisions are copied and have to be transfered over the network when the transaction is committed. And this is the point where I'd like to analyze the delta between the baseline revision and the modified one to reduce the network payload.

