Here's my $0.02:
I like the idea of using a common pattern in the viewer and in commands.  But in the end, I don't think there is actually that much differences between the two approaches.  Both have their advantages, and both have their drawbacks.  In this situation, whatever is most familiar and established pattern is probably the best choice.  With that in mind, I would suggest following:

1) Request to have two new interfaces created in org.eclipse.core.runtime:

    interface IRequestMonitor {
        public void done();
        public void cancel();
        public boolean isCancelled();
    }

    interface IStatusMonitor extends IRequestMonitor {
        public void setStatus(IStatus status);
        public IStatus getStatus();
    }

And have the IProgressMonitor extend IRequestMonitor.  This would avoid creating a duplicate interface and would be a backward-compatible change so it might be an easy sell.

2) Choose either of the patterns: 
    executeCommandXYZ(IRequestMonitor monitor) {
        ...
        monitor.done();
    }
or
    executeCommand(IXYZRequest request) {
        ...
        request.getMonitor().done();
    }
and use it in both the flexible hierarchy viewer and in commands.  I'm don't know which is better, although my guess is that the first one is more familiar to people because it's more common, while the latter is probably easier for the framework to implement against.
----

A couple of other comments on the patch:  I don't know if it makes sense to have a IRequest.begin() method.  It seems to me that it's safe to assume that the processing of the request begins when the provider is called with the request.  Also, in my view the IRequest.add/removeRequestListener() methods are an implementation detail of the Request class and should be left out of the IRequestMonitor interface.

