Let us suppose we have a class called Socket.java.  We view the AST representation and we wish to import this class to a different file.  If we view the AST representation of Socket.java as an imported class, we do not have the same level of detail as viewing the class on its own (modifier data is missing).

Consider the following example.  We can see the annotation modifier in the AST in package p, but cannot see it as an imported file.

package p;
public @interface MyAnnot {
        String value();
}

package x;

import
p.*;
public class A {
        @MyAnnot ("hello")
        public A() {        
        }
}

package y;

import x.A; // open ast view here and look at method modifiers

public class B {
        public void foo() {
                new A(); // or open it here and look at method modifiers
        }
} 

